[1] Cholera - PAHO report
Date: Fri 24 Jun 2015
Source: Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) [edited]
http://www.paho.org/hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&Itemid=270&gid=30752&lang=en


Cholera in the Americas - situation summary
-------------------------------------------
Since the beginning of 2015 up to epidemiological week (EW) 22 of 2015 [week ending 5 Jun 2015], a total of 16 961 cases have been reported in 3 countries in the Region of the Americas: Haiti (16 687 cases), the Dominican Republic (273 cases), and Cuba (1 case).

The last confirmed case of cholera in Cuba was reported in January 2015, and was reported by the Canada International Health Regulations (IHR) National Focal Point. The case was an individual with history of travel to Cuba.

In the Dominican Republic, in 2014 there were 597 suspected cholera cases recorded, including 10 deaths, which represents a 70 percent reduction in the number of cases and 76 percent reduction in the number of deaths in comparison to 2013. Between epidemiological week (EW) 1 and EW 20 of 2015 [3 Jan-22 May 2015], there were 273 suspected cholera cases registered, including 10 deaths. This represents an increase of 76 percent of the cases recorded for the same period of 2014. This situation in the Dominican Republic is linked to the cholera trends registered in Haiti during the same period. Since the beginning of the epidemic (November 2010) to EW 20 of 2015, a total of 32 358 suspected cholera cases, including 488 deaths, have been recorded in the Dominican Republic.

In Haiti, since the beginning of the epidemic (October 2010) through 31 Mar 2015, there were 738 528 cholera cases, of which 421 013 were hospitalized (57 percent cumulative hospitalization rate), and 8925 deaths. The cumulative case fatality rate remains at 1.2 percent. From EW 1 to EW 22 of 2015 [3 Jan-5 Jun 2015], there were 16 696 cholera cases, including 13 304 hospitalizations (80 percent hospitalization rate), and 140 deaths (case fatality rate of 0.8 percent). The number of cases and deaths reported by epidemiological week in 2015 are showing an increase in comparison to the number recorded in the same period of 2014. In addition, in some weeks of 2015 the number of cases recorded is greater than what was recorded in 2012 as demonstrated in Figure 1 [for figures, see source URL above. - Mod.LL]. Between the months of May and June [2015], the Haiti Ministry of Public Health and Population (MSPP) has reported outbreak alerts in 4 out of 10 departments in the country.

Cholera is closely related to adequate access to sanitation and drinking water, and for this reason, controlling the disease remains a challenge in countries where there is poor access to sanitation and drinking water. The Pan American Health Organization / World Health Organization (PAHO/WHO) encourages Member States to remain vigilant and continue implementing the activities PAHO/WHO has recommended since November 2012.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

