[2] Cholera - UK ex Cuba
Date: Wed 1 Jul 2015
From: Nicholas Beeching <Nicholas.beeching@rlbuht.nhs.uk> [edited]


We write to alert colleagues to the continued presence of cholera in Cuba and to the need to consider this in the differential diagnosis of travellers returning with diarrhoea from that area.

We are treating a 60 year old UK resident who recently returned from a 14 day all inclusive holiday in one of the quality tourist hotels in Varadero, Cuba. He had short lived diarrhea about 6 days after arriving in Cuba in early June 2015, but this disappeared rapidly. On the day of his return to the UK he felt generally unwell and developed profuse diarrhea, but managed to catch the plane home. He continued to have watery diarrhea up to 50 times in a 24 hour period and after 5 days he developed postural dizziness, his blood pressure was reduced to 77/54 and his urine output was greatly reduced. He was admitted to our unit with hypotension and acute kidney injury, which have responded well to IV and oral rehydration. Culture of feces revealed _Aeromonas veronii_, _Vibrio cholerae_ (sensitive to ciprofloxacin and doxycycline), and another _Vibrio_ sp, full identities to be confirmed. He is being treated with oral ciprofloxacin to cover all these organisms, with excellent response.

He had been on a day trip to Havana 2 days before he became ill. His wife, who accompanied him throughout his holiday, remains well but several other people staying in his hotel (not necessarily in the same tour group) had reported severe gastroenteritis symptoms with a similar period of onset. We have notified his case to the GeoSentinel network as a reporting centre and to Public Health England, who will presumably pass details on to the Cuban authorities. We have omitted from this public report the precise details of his travel dates and the resort hotel to allow the relevant authorities to carry out any investigations without prejudice. A 2nd traveler from the same tour group has just been admitted to our unit with prolonged diarrhea, the aetiology of which is being investigated.

After decades with no cases of cholera, the infection reached Cuba again in 2012 [see ProMED-mail archive 20120702.1187070]. By the middle of 2014 over 700 cases had been reported, including travellers returning to North America and to Europe [1,2], but with few local cases after 2013 [see ProMED-mail archive 20130911.1936068]. We have not seen cholera from Cuba before, but our case follows recent reports of a traveler returning to Canada with cholera [3]. This suggests that there is still cholera transmission in Cuba and that this should be considered in travelers returning from Cuba as well as from neighboring countries in the Caribbean, including Mexico [4].

References
----------
1. Mascarello M, Deiana ML, Maurel C, et al: Cholera with severe renal failure in an Italian tourist returning from Cuba, July 2013. Euro Surveill. 29 Aug 2013; 18(35):pii=20572; http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=20572.

2. CDC: Cholera in Cuba. Reviewed 26 May 2015 http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/watch/cholera-cuba [This notice has been removed from the CDC Travel Notices page (29 Jun 2015)].

3. Public Health Agency of Canada: Travel Health Notice: Cholera in Cuba, Dominican Republic, Haiti and Mexico. Updated 20 March 2015; http://phac-aspc.gc.ca/tmp-pmv/notices-avis/notices-avis-eng.php?id=111.

4. Fillion K, Mileno MD: Cholera in travelers: shifting tides in epidemiology, management, and prevention. Curr Infect Dis Rep. 2015;17(1):455. doi: 10.1007/s11908-014-0455-4. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25604481.

[Authors: Derek Cocker, Nick Beeching, Godfrey Smith, Mike Beadsworth]

--
Dr Nicholas Beeching
Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine,
Royal Liverpool University Hospital and
NIHR Health Protection Research Unit in Emerging and Zoonotic Infections,
