<Nicholas.beeching@rlbuht.nhs.uk>

[Maps of Cuba can be seen at http://ateliers.revues.org/docannexe/image/9447/img-1-small580.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3480336,25128. Varadero is a resort town in Cuba's province of Matanzas, and one of the largest resort areas in the Caribbean. It is unclear where the __V. cholerae_ infection was acquired but others ill at the hotel suggest it may be from the hotel in Matanzas rather than from Havana, 70 miles (113 km) away.

ProMED-mail thanks Dr Beeching for this report. This is the second report of cholera acquired in Cuba, neither was reported by Cuba but rather from the country that the tourist returned to. Cholera has been likely occurring in the island nation since re-introduced probably by Cuban physicians travelling back from Haiti in June 2012. - Mod.LL]

******
[3] Cholera - Mexico (Sonora State)
Date: Thu 18 Jun 2015
Source: UNO TV [in Spanish, trans. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
http://www.unotv.com/noticias/estados/noroeste/registran-primer-caso-de-colera-en-sur-de-sonora-395731/


Sanitary District number 5 in the municipality of Navojoa reported the 1st case of cholera [in Sonora state] so far in 2015. The head of the Sanitary District, Martin Ruy Sanchez Toledo, said the patient is a 46-year-old man from the community of Pozo Dulce, in the municipality of Huatabampo, in the south of the state.

The sample was taken on 2 Jun 2015 and tested positive by results. Surveillance in the community revealed no other cases.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

It is unclear what is known about the Sonoran isolate regarding whether it is a O1 (or O139). Non-O1, non-O139 _V. cholerae_ does occur along the coasts of USA and Mexico, generally (but not always) causing milder illness without the epidemic potential. - Mod.LL

Maps of Mexico can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/northamerica/political-map-of-Mexico.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3480336,509. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ
